[b]Relative Strength Line — trade what is stronger than the market[/b]

[b]What it does[/b]
Most indicators measure a symbol in isolation. This one measures it [i]relative to a benchmark[/i] — SPY, QQQ, or any symbol you choose — because that is the dimension institutions actually trade: they accumulate what is stronger than the index. It plots the classic RS line (price ÷ benchmark) or the normalized Mansfield RS oscillator, and flags the IBD leadership signal: relative strength making a new high [i]before[/i] price does.

[b]Display modes[/b]
[list]
[*]Mansfield RS (default) — a normalized oscillator around zero: the percentage distance of the RS line from its own moving average. Above zero = outperforming the benchmark; below zero = lagging.
[*]Raw RS Line — the price-to-benchmark ratio itself, with its moving average. The slope is what matters, not the absolute level.
[/list]

[b]Leadership signal[/b]
[list]
[*]RS breaks to a new high while price has not yet → relative strength is leading the move (bullish accumulation). Marked with an "RS" triangle.
[*]RS breaks down before price → distribution warning.
[/list]

[b]Trend state[/b]
Derived from the Mansfield value and its slope: Leading rising, Leading fading, Lagging improving, Lagging falling.

[b]Dashboard[/b]
Benchmark, current state, Mansfield percentage, leadership status, and an RS rank (0–100) showing where current relative strength sits within the lookback range.

[b]Alerts[/b]
RS leadership up · RS leadership down · Mansfield crossing above zero · Mansfield crossing below zero.

[b]Best for[/b]
Momentum equities where relative strength vs. the index is the primary stock-selection filter. Use QQQ as the benchmark for tech/momentum names, SPY for the broad market.

